<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43469323" data-cid="43469323">
    <div id="comment_43469323">
        <header data-points="3" data-reason="Interesting">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="PV with 40% conversion rates"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>PV with 40% conversion rates<span> (3, Interesting)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~Taco+Cowboy" class="author" title="author name and user ID">Taco Cowboy (5327) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3655223&cid=43469323">(#43469323)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43469323" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="3" data-reason="Interesting">
            <div class="comment-body"><div class="quote"><p><i>Actually, depending on how you define best (do laboratory samples count?) I think they're past 40% now</i></p></div><p> If you read closely on how they achieve the more than 40% efficiency you would see that they are not "1 sun" PV structure</p><p>Case in point, Solar Junction ( <a href="http://www.sj-solar.com/" title="sj-solar.com">http://www.sj-solar.com/</a> <span class="domain-text"> [sj-solar.com]</span>  ) came out with the "lattice matched 942X" which has 44% conversion rate</p><p>That "942X" denotes "942 suns", which means, the PV from Solar Junction is not flat panel type of PV, but rather, achieve its high efficiency with the use of <i>focusing optics</i></p><p>Allow me to quote from <a href="http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2012/10/solar-junction-does-it-again-sets-new-cpv-efficiency-record" title="renewableenergyworld.com">http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2012/10/solar-junction-does-it-again-sets-new-cpv-efficiency-record</a> <span class="domain-text"> [renewableenergyworld.com]</span> </p><p><i>"<nobr> <wbr></nobr>... Think of a magnifying glass. Basically, you have a very high performance solar cell that sits at the focal point of these focusing optics. The solar cell converts the photon flux into electrons, and power</i></p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_43469323">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="3655223" data-cid="43469323">
                    <button class="btn btn-default call-form" data-sid="43469323" data-pid="43469323" data-cid="43469323"><i class="fa fa-reply"></i> Reply</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-default show-parent" href=""><i class="fa fa-level-up"></i> Parent</button>
