<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_43469281" data-cid="43469281">
    <div id="comment_43469281">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Transparent conductors?"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Transparent conductors?<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~Okian+Warrior" class="author" title="author name and user ID">Okian Warrior (537106) </a> | about a year ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3655223&cid=43469281">(#43469281)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_43469281" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>Don't PV panels require a transparent conductor as a top layer? Something that lets the light through and conducts away the electricity?</p><p>Once the side of your house is painted with this stuff, how would you gather the energy?</p><p>Cheap photovoltaic molecules is part of the problem. We still need a cheap transparent conductor to gather the generated energy.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_43469281">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="3655223" data-cid="43469281">
